You have declared new _local_ variables to store the input data, rather than assigning to the instance variables.

```
    public void read() {     
        Scanner in  = new Scanner(System.in);
        
        System.out.println(&quot;Product name: &quot;);
        name = in.nextLine(); 
        System.out.println(&quot;Price: &quot;);
        price = in.nextDouble();
        System.out.println(&quot;Score: &quot;);
        core = in.nextInt();
    }
```

In the read method you have created local variables for name price and core. You are reading into these local variables instead of into the member variables (fields) of your class.

Instead of

```java
        String name = in.nextLine(); 
        double price = in.nextDouble();
        int core = in.nextInt();
```

You should do

```java
        this.name = in.nextLine(); 
        this.price = in.nextDouble();
        this.core = in.nextInt();
```

Now that we&#39;ve removed the local variables we are no longer shadowing the instance variables. We can therefore omit `this.` in the solution above so could do

```java
        name = in.nextLine(); 
        price = in.nextDouble();
        core = in.nextInt();
```

