You can override the `dataSource` method in `TestConfig` for one test without affecting other tests by using the `@Primary` annotation in the configuration class specific to that test. Here&#39;s an example:

Create a test-specific configuration class, call `TestSpecificConfig`, which takes an instance of `TestConfig`:

```java
@Configuration
public class TestSpecificConfig extends TestConfig {

     @Primary
     @Bean
     public DataSource dataSource() {
         final var hikariDataSource = new HikariDataSource();
         hikariDataSource.setJdbcUrl(&quot;jdbc:tc:postgresql:15:///databasename&quot;);
         return hikariDataSource;
     }
}
```

Within your test class (`RateLimiterTest`), use the `@ContextConfiguration` annotation to define a test-specific configuration class:

```java
@WebAppConfiguration
@ContextConfiguration(classes = {TestSpecificConfig.class})
public class RateLimiterTest extends AbstractJUnit4SpringContextTests {

     // ... the rest of your test code
}
```

This way, you create a custom configuration for your test (`TestSpecificConfig`) that replaces the `dataSource` method with the desired implementation. The `@Primary` annotation ensures that this bean has a higher priority than the one defined in the base `TestConfig` during test execution.

